<!-- TIMELINE -->
<section id="timeline">
  <div class="timeline-inner">
    <div class="section-label">Since 1988</div>
    <h2 class="timeline-heading">A History of Discovery</h2>
    <p class="timeline-intro">
      From a single faculty appointment to a global research enterprise, this timeline traces the pivotal moments that shaped CHOPR's mission and amplified its influence on health policy worldwide.
    </p>

    <div class="timeline-track" id="timeline-track">

      <!-- 1988 -->
      <div class="tl-event left milestone">
        <div class="tl-card">
          <div class="tl-card-category">Founding</div>
          <h3>Linda Aiken Joins Penn as Trustee Professor</h3>
          <p>Dr. Linda H. Aiken was appointed as a University of Pennsylvania Trustee Professor — one of the institution's highest honors — bringing with her a bold vision for health services research centered on nursing and patient outcomes.</p>
          <span class="tl-tag">Penn Nursing</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-node">
          <div class="tl-dot"></div>
          <div class="tl-year">1988</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-empty"></div>
      </div>

      <!-- 1989 -->
      <div class="tl-event right milestone">
        <div class="tl-empty"></div>
        <div class="tl-node">
          <div class="tl-dot"></div>
          <div class="tl-year">1989</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-card">
          <div class="tl-card-category">Founding</div>
          <h3>CHOPR Is Established</h3>
          <p>Dr. Aiken formally established the Center for Health Outcomes and Policy Research to explore organizational effectiveness in health care with the potential to affect patient outcomes — a mission that would define the field.</p>
          <span class="tl-tag">Center Launch</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 1993 -->
      <div class="tl-event left">
        <div class="tl-card">
          <div class="tl-card-category">Policy</div>
          <h3>Aiken Named Co-Chair of the Health Care Workforce Subcommittee</h3>
          <p>During the Clinton Administration's national health care reform effort, Dr. Aiken was appointed co-chair of the Health Care Workforce Subcommittee, positioning CHOPR research at the center of federal health policy debate.</p>
          <span class="tl-tag">Federal Policy</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-node">
          <div class="tl-dot"></div>
          <div class="tl-year">1993</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-empty"></div>
      </div>

      <!-- 1997 -->
      <div class="tl-event right milestone">
        <div class="tl-empty"></div>
        <div class="tl-node">
          <div class="tl-dot"></div>
          <div class="tl-year">1997</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-card">
          <div class="tl-card-category">Training</div>
          <h3>NIH T32 Training Grant Established</h3>
          <p>The National Institutes of Health funded CHOPR's predoctoral training program in nursing outcomes research — initiating a pipeline that would produce more than 85 doctoral-trained scholars, the vast majority of whom went on to research-intensive careers.</p>
          <span class="tl-tag">NIH · NINR</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 1999 -->
      <div class="tl-event left">
        <div class="tl-card">
          <div class="tl-card-category">Landmark Report</div>
          <h3>IOM Releases "To Err is Human"</h3>
          <p>The Institute of Medicine's landmark report on preventable medical errors galvanized national attention on patient safety and hospital care quality — validating CHOPR's long-standing focus on the organizational drivers of patient outcomes and amplifying demand for its research.</p>
          <span class="tl-tag">Patient Safety</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-node">
          <div class="tl-dot"></div>
          <div class="tl-year">1999</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-empty"></div>
      </div>

      <!-- 2002 -->
      <div class="tl-event right milestone">
        <div class="tl-empty"></div>
        <div class="tl-node">
          <div class="tl-dot"></div>
          <div class="tl-year">2002</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-card">
          <div class="tl-card-category">Science → Policy</div>
          <h3>Landmark JAMA Study Links Nurse Staffing to Patient Mortality</h3>
          <p>Aiken and CHOPR colleagues published a seminal study in <em>JAMA</em> demonstrating that each additional patient per nurse was associated with a 7% increase in the likelihood of patient death — among the most influential papers in health services research and a direct catalyst for staffing legislation.</p>
          <span class="tl-tag">JAMA · Nurse Staffing</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 2004 -->
      <div class="tl-event left">
        <div class="tl-card">
          <div class="tl-card-category">Work Environment</div>
          <h3>Magnet Hospital Research Advances Work Environment Science</h3>
          <p>CHOPR published influential studies establishing the relationship between the professional practice environment — including nurse autonomy, physician-nurse relations, and managerial support — and both nurse outcomes and patient outcomes, informing the Magnet Recognition Program's evidence base.</p>
          <span class="tl-tag">Magnet · Work Environment</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-node">
          <div class="tl-dot"></div>
          <div class="tl-year">2004</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-empty"></div>
      </div>

      <!-- 2005 -->
      <div class="tl-event right">
        <div class="tl-empty"></div>
        <div class="tl-node">
          <div class="tl-dot"></div>
          <div class="tl-year">2005</div>
